Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /e.oː/
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /e.o/, [ɛ.ɔ] (stressed on the antepenult)

Etymology 1[edit]

From Proto-Italic *-ēō, from verbs with Proto-Indo-European *-éh₁yeti (stative suffix).

Suffix[edit]

-eō (present infinitive -ēre); second conjugation, no perfect or supine stem

  2. Forms stative verbs from adjectives.

Etymology 2[edit]

From Proto-Italic *-eō, from causative / frequentative verbs with Proto-Indo-European *-éyeti (causative suffix).

Suffix[edit]

-eō (present infinitive -ēre); second conjugation, no perfect or supine stem

  2. (no longer productive) Forms causative verbs from primary (third conjugation and some fourth conjugation) verbs.

Etymology 3[edit]

See the etymology of the main entry.

Suffix[edit]

-eō

  1. dative masculine singular of -eus
  2. dative neuter singular of -eus
  3. ablative masculine singular of -eus
  4. ablative neuter singular of -eus
